article.headline: 15-2 second-half run propels Tigers
article.linkText: No. 18 LSU wins its eighth straight
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Temple coach Dawn Staley knew that for
the Owls to upset LSU (No. 18 ESPN/USA Today, No. 17 AP), they would have to slow down the
backcourt trio of Seimone Augustus, Temeka Johnson and Doneeka
Hodges.

Staley, a two-time Olympian and three-time WNBA all-star, had a
plan, but it wasn't good enough.

Temeka Johnson had 15 points and 12 rebounds, and LSU beat
Temple 68-52 Monday night for its eighth consecutive victory.

Seimone Augustus led the Tigers (9-2) with 19 points, and
Doneeka Hodges added 17 and eight rebounds. Hodges was carried off
the floor with 1:42 remaining when she slipped and hurt her left
ankle.

"They are very perimeter heavy, and they are the heart and soul
of their team," Staley said. "We knew coming in what kind of game
it would be, and we did not do that as often as our game plan
called for."

Candice Dupree led Temple (3-4) with 19 points. The Owls cut a
nine-point deficit to 31-27 with three minutes left in the first
half, but lost a chance to get closer with a shot-clock violation.

"When you don't stay disciplined against a team like this, it
will open up on you really quickly," Staley said.

LSU followed with baskets from Augustus and Hodges, and
Johnson's running 30-footer capped a 7-0 run to make it 38-27 at
the break.

"We knew we couldn't allow Temple to grab momentum," Johnson
said.

Cynthia Jordan hit a 3-pointer to open the second half to pull
the Owls within eight. But the Tigers outscored the Owls 15-2 over
the next three minutes, taking a 53-32 lead on Hodges' layup with
13:38 remaining.

"I thought we really had a couple of chances to put the game
away," LSU coach Sue Gunter said. "We played very well at times,
but at other times, we went into a dry spell."
